# Team Baseline Coding Standards

## Purpose
This rule establishes baseline coding conventions for the team. It applies to all TypeScript and JavaScript files.

## Standards

### Naming Conventions
- Use `camelCase` for variables, functions, and methods
- Use `PascalCase` for classes, interfaces, types, and React components
- Use `UPPER_SNAKE_CASE` for constants
- Prefix interfaces with `I` only when needed to avoid naming conflicts
- Use descriptive names that reveal intent

### Code Organization
- One export per file for components and classes
- Group imports: external libraries, then internal modules, then relative imports
- Keep files under 300 lines; split if larger
- Place types and interfaces at the top of files or in separate `.types.ts` files

### Error Handling
- Always handle errors explicitly; never silently catch and ignore
- Use typed error classes for domain-specific errors
- Include context in error messages
- Log errors with sufficient detail for debugging

### Comments and Documentation
- Document public APIs with JSDoc comments
- Explain "why" not "what" in inline comments
- Keep TODOs actionable with owner and context
- Remove commented-out code before committing

## Correct Example

```typescript
// Good: Descriptive names, proper structure
interface UserProfile {
  id: string;
  displayName: string;
  email: string;
  createdAt: Date;
}

const MAX_RETRY_ATTEMPTS = 3;

export class UserService {
  /**
   * Retrieves a user profile by ID.
   * @param userId - The unique user identifier
   * @returns The user profile or null if not found
   * @throws {DatabaseError} If database connection fails
   */
  async getUserById(userId: string): Promise<UserProfile | null> {
    try {
      return await this.repository.findById(userId);
    } catch (error) {
      throw new DatabaseError(`Failed to fetch user ${userId}`, { cause: error });
    }
  }
}
```

## Incorrect Example

```typescript
// Bad: Poor naming, no error handling, no documentation
interface user {  // Should be PascalCase
  id: any;        // Avoid any type
  n: string;      // Non-descriptive name
}

export class usr {  // Poor class name
  // Missing JSDoc
  async get(x: string) {  // Non-descriptive parameter
    try {
      return await this.r.find(x);
    } catch (e) {
      // Silent failure - never do this
    }
  }
}
```

## Enforcement
- This rule is enforced during code review
- Violations should be flagged by Cursor during editing
- Critical violations block merge approval
